Follow @inspiring.engineering for more. 🔥A lithophane✨
A lithophane is an etched or molded artwork in very thin translucent porcelain or plastic that can be seen clearly only when back lit with a light source

Lithophanes are essentially embossed photos generated by a 3D printer. The print results don’t show much at first, but shine some light through one and you’ll be amazed by the details. The way it works is that light passes through the thin parts while being blocked by the thick parts. In this way, the differences in light bring out the details of the image.

There are many tools for turning your photo into a lithophane model, but virtually all of them work the same way. First, they guess the primary object of the photo and emboss it. Then they give it a nice border and provide you the final file in a 3D format like STL.

Follow @inspiring.engineering for more. 🔥The world’s first paper razor (because disposable razors aren't doing the planet any favours) ⠀
⠀
We’ve seen razors made of recycled plastics or 100% plastic-free, but Japanese brand Kai has made a disposable razor from paper inspired by origami and milk cartons. The flat-pack body razor comes with a metal blade, which is easily assembled in a matter of seconds by merely folding in the sides and the top. ⠀
⠀
Like us, you’re probably wondering how does a paper razor work with water? Well, Kai Group has used a relatively water-resistant grade of paper - the type used for milk cartons or cardboard paper-spoons. It might not be the ultimate solution but it does reduce the use of plastic by 98% and it is a good alternative for those disposable all-plastic razors.  ⠀
